cestershire placename derives from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>dīc</i>. Reddish in Lymm (Cheshire) derives from Old English <i>rūh</i> ‘rough’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure’. Reddish in Taxal (Cheshire) probably has the same etymology as the Lancashire placename."],"variants":[{"name":"Redish","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aaron David, Mendel.","English: variant of   Reddish  .","Jewish (from Bohemia; also <b>Redisch</b>): from the Yiddish name for the town Hradišt in Bohemia."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cecily Reddish was born about 1180, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert de Reddish. She married Robert Shoresworth. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1180–":"umbes 1180–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1210–1262":"1210–1262","–1242":"–1242","–1281":"–1281","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1210":"1210","1242":"1242","1262":"1262","1140":"1140","1281":"1281","Abt 1180":"umbes 1180","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1180–":"noin 1180–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1210–1262":"1210–1262","–1242":"–1242","–1281":"–1281","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","Abt 1210":"noin 1210","1210":"1210","1242":"1242","1262":"1262","1140":"1140","1281":"1281","Abt 1180":"noin 1180","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1180–":"environ 1180–Dé